          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Why are long bone fractures extremely painful?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Why are long bone fractures extremely painful?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The medullary cavity contains pressure-sensitive marrow that is compressed during fracture</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The medullary cavity holds yellow fatty marrow in adults and red marrow in children. Marrow is not richly innervated with sensory fibres and does not account for fracture pain.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The articular cartilage at the bone ends has abundant sensory nerve endings</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Articular cartilage is avascular and aneural — it has no blood supply, no nerves, and no lymphatics. It cannot transmit pain signals.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The periosteum covering the bone surface is richly innervated with sensory fibres</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The periosteum is a fibrous sheet covering the outer surface of bone and carries a dense sensory nerve supply. When a fracture disrupts the periosteum, these nerve endings are stimulated intensely. Compact bone and marrow receive mainly vasomotor sympathetic fibres, not sensory ones.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The compact bone of the diaphysis contains dense nociceptive fibres throughout its matrix</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Compact bone itself receives mainly vasomotor sympathetic fibres, not sensory nociceptive fibres. The pain of a fracture arises from the richly innervated periosteum, not the bone matrix.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The key point is that the periosteum, the fibrous covering of bone, is richly innervated with sensory nerve endings. Compact bone and marrow receive mainly vasomotor sympathetic fibres, not sensory ones."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The periosteum is the most pain-sensitive structure in bone — this is why fractures, periosteal stripping, and subperiosteal infections are so painful."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
