          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In endochondral ossification, where does the primary centre of ossification firs</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In endochondral ossification, where does the primary centre of ossification first appear?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>In the metaphysis, at the epiphyseal growth plate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The metaphysis contains the growth plate, which is the interface between the primary and secondary ossification centres. The primary centre itself does not originate here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>In the periosteum, by direct mesenchymal conversion</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Direct conversion of mesenchyme into bone without a cartilage model describes intramembranous ossification, not endochondral. Intramembranous ossification forms the flat skull bones and the clavicle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>In the epiphysis, usually after birth</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The epiphyses are where secondary centres of ossification appear, usually after birth. The primary centre appears much earlier, in a different region of the bone.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>In the diaphysis, during foetal life</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. In endochondral ossification, the primary centre appears in the diaphysis (shaft) during foetal life, replacing the hyaline cartilage model with bone. Secondary centres then appear in the epiphyses, usually after birth.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "In endochondral ossification, the primary centre appears in the diaphysis during foetal life. Secondary centres appear later in the epiphyses, usually after birth. This sequence underlies the three laws of long bone ossification."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Remembering that the primary centre appears in the diaphysis during foetal life helps you understand why the diaphysis is the most ossified part of a newborn's long bone on X-ray."
                }
              ],
