          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>According to Hilton's Law, hip joint pathology can present as knee pain. Which n</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>According to Hilton's Law, hip joint pathology can present as knee pain. Which nerve is responsible for this referred pain pattern?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sciatic nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The sciatic nerve (through its tibial and common peroneal branches) supplies the hamstrings and the knee joint. However, it is not the nerve classically responsible for the referred pain from hip to knee described in the video.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Obturator nerve</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The obturator nerve supplies muscles acting on both the hip joint and the knee joint. By Hilton's Law, it therefore innervates both joints. Pain from hip pathology can be referred along the obturator nerve to the knee — a classic clinical trap in orthopaedics.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh is a purely sensory nerve supplying skin on the lateral thigh. It does not supply either the hip or knee joint and plays no role in this referred pain pattern.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Tibial nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The tibial nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve that supplies muscles below the knee. It does not supply the hip joint and cannot explain the hip-to-knee referred pain pattern.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The obturator nerve supplies muscles acting on both the hip and knee joints. By Hilton's Law, the same nerve that supplies a muscle acting on a joint also supplies that joint itself — so hip pathology can refer pain to the knee through the shared obturator nerve supply."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly. The obturator nerve supplying both joints is the classic example of Hilton's Law in clinical practice. Always consider hip pathology when a child presents with unexplained knee pain."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
